# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vhdl-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] In computer engineering, a **hardware description language** (**HDL**) is a specialized computer language used to describe the structure and behavior of electronic circuits, usually to design application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) and to program field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs).
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] A hardware description language enables a precise, formal description of an electronic circuit that allows for the automated analysis and simulation of the circuit.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] It also allows for the synthesis of an HDL description into a netlist (a specification of physical electronic components and how they are connected together), which can then be placed and routed to produce the set of masks used to create an integrated circuit.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] A hardware description language looks much like a programming language such as C or ALGOL; it is a textual description consisting of expressions, statements and control structures.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] One important difference between most programming languages and HDLs is that HDLs explicitly include the notion of time.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] HDLs form an integral part of electronic design automation (EDA) systems, especially for complex circuits, such as application-specific integrated circuits, microprocessors, and programmable logic devices.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] HDLs were created to implement register-transfer level abstraction, a model of the dataflow and timing of a circuit.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Two major hardware description languages exist: VHDL and Verilog.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] In them, three different types of description occur: *dataflow*, *behavioral*, and *structural*.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] HDLs are standard text-based expressions of the structure of electronic systems and their behaviour over time.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Like concurrent programming languages, HDL syntax and semantics include explicit notations for expressing concurrency.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] However, in contrast to most software programming languages, HDLs also include an explicit notion of time, which is a primary attribute of hardware.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Languages whose only characteristic is to express circuit connectivity between a hierarchy of blocks are properly classified as netlist languages used in electric computer-aided design.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] HDL can be used to express designs in structural, behavioral or register-transfer-level architectures for the same circuit functionality; in the latter two cases the synthesizer decides the architecture and logic gate layout.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] HDLs are used to write executable specifications for hardware.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] A program designed to implement the underlying semantics of the language statements and simulate the progress of time provides the hardware designer with the ability to model a piece of hardware before it is created physically.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] It is this executability that gives HDLs the illusion of being programming languages, when they are more precisely classified as specification languages or modeling languages.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Simulators capable of supporting discrete-event (digital) and continuous-time (analog) modeling exist, and HDLs targeted for each are available.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] It is certainly possible to represent hardware semantics using traditional programming languages such as C++, which operate on control flow semantics in contrast to dataflow, although to function as such, programs must be augmented with extensive and unwieldy class libraries.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Generally, however, software programming languages include no ability to express time explicitly, and thus cannot function as hardware description languages.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Before the debut of System Verilog in 2002, C++ integration with a logic simulator was one of the few ways to use object-oriented programming in hardware verification.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] System Verilog is the first major HDL to offer object-orientation and garbage collection.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Using the proper subset of hardware description language, a program called a synthesizer, or logic synthesis tool, can infer hardware logic operations from the language statements and produce an equivalent netlist of generic hardware primitives to implement the specified behaviour.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Synthesizers generally ignore the expression of any timing constructs in the text.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Digital logic synthesizers, for example, generally use clock edges as the way to time the circuit, ignoring any timing constructs.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The ability to have a synthesizable subset of the language does not itself make a hardware description language.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The first hardware description languages appeared in the late 1960s, looking like more traditional languages.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The first that had a lasting effect was described in 1971 in C.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Gordon Bell and Allen Newell's text *Computer Structures*.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] This text introduced the concept of register transfer level, first used in the ISP language to describe the behavior of the Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-8.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The language became more widespread with the introduction of DEC's PDP-16 RT-Level Modules (RTMs) and a book describing their use.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] At least two implementations of the basic ISP language (ISPL and ISPS) followed.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] ISPS was well suited to describe relations between the inputs and the outputs of the design and was quickly adopted by commercial teams at DEC, and by several research teams in the US and among its allies in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The RTM products never succeeded commercially and DEC stopped marketing them in the mid-1980s, as new methods grew more popular, more so very-large-scale integration (VLSI).
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Separate work done about 1979 at the University of Kaiserslautern produced a language named *KAiserslautern Register Transfer Language* (KARL), which included design calculus language features supporting VLSI chip floorplanning and structured hardware design.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] This work was also the basis of KARL's interactive graphic sister language ABL, whose name was an initialism for "a block diagram language".
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] ABL was implemented in the early 1980s by the Centro Studi e Laboratori Telecomunicazioni (CSELT) in Torino, Italy, producing the ABLED graphic VLSI design editor.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] In the mid-1980s, a VLSI design framework was implemented around KARL and ABL by an international consortium funded by the Commission of the European Union.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] By the late 1970s, design using programmable logic devices (PLDs) became popular, although these designs were primarily limited to designing finite-state machines.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The work at Data General in 1980 used these same devices to design the Data General Eclipse MV/8000, and commercial need began to grow for a language that could map well to them.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] By 1983 Data I/O introduced ABEL to fill that need.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] In 1985, as design shifted to VLSI, Gateway Design Automation introduced Verilog, and Intermetrics released the first completed version of the VHSIC Hardware Description Language (VHDL).
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] VHDL was developed at the behest of the United States Department of Defense's Very High Speed Integrated Circuit Program (VHSIC), and was based on the Ada programming language, and on the experience gained with the earlier development of ISPS.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Initially, Verilog and VHDL were used to document and simulate circuit designs already captured and described in another form (such as schematic files).
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] HDL simulation enabled designers to work at a higher level of abstraction than simulation at the schematic level, and thus increased design capacity from hundreds of transistors to thousands.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] In 1986, with the support of the U.S Department of Defense, VHDL was sponsored as an IEEE standard (IEEE Std 1076), and the first IEEE-standardized version of VHDL, IEEE Std 1076-1987, was approved in December 1987.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Cadence Design Systems later acquired Gateway Design Automation for the rights to Verilog-XL, the HDL simulator that would become the de facto standard of Verilog simulators for the next decade.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The introduction of logic synthesis for HDLs pushed HDLs from the background into the foreground of digital design.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Synthesis tools compiled HDL source code files (written in a constrained format named RTL) into a manufacturable netlist description in terms of logic gates and transistors.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Writing synthesizable RTL files required practice and discipline on the part of the designer; compared to a traditional schematic layout, synthesized RTL netlists were almost always larger in area and slower in performance.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Within a few years, VHDL and Verilog emerged as the dominant HDLs in the electronics industry, while older and less capable HDLs gradually disappeared from use.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] However, VHDL and Verilog share many of the same limits, such as being unsuitable for analog or mixed-signal circuit simulation.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Specialized HDLs (such as Confluence) were introduced with the explicit goal of fixing specific limits of Verilog and VHDL, though none were ever intended to replace them.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Over the years, much effort has been invested in improving HDLs.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The latest iteration of Verilog, formally named IEEE 1800-2005 SystemVerilog, introduces many new features (classes, random variables, and properties/assertions) to address the growing need for better test bench randomization, design hierarchy, and reuse.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] A future revision of VHDL is also in development, and is expected to match SystemVerilog's improvements.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] As a result of the efficiency gains realized using HDL, a majority of modern digital circuit design revolves around it.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Most designs begin as a set of requirements or a high-level architectural diagram.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Control and decision structures are often prototyped in flowchart applications, or entered in a editor.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The process of writing the HDL description is highly dependent on the nature of the circuit and the designer's preference for coding style.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The HDL is merely the 'capture language', often beginning with a high-level algorithmic description such as a C++ mathematical model.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Designers often use scripting languages such as Perl to automatically generate repetitive circuit structures in the HDL language.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Special text editors offer features for automatic indentation, syntax-dependent coloration, and macro-based expansion of the entity/architecture/signal declaration.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The HDL code then undergoes a code review, or auditing.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] In preparation for synthesis, the HDL description is subject to an array of automated checkers.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The checkers report deviations from standardized code guidelines, identify potential ambiguous code constructs before they can cause misinterpretation, and check for common logical coding errors, such as floating ports or shorted outputs.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] This process aids in resolving errors before the code is synthesized.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] In industry parlance, HDL design generally ends at the synthesis stage.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Once the synthesis tool has mapped the HDL description into a gate netlist, the netlist is passed off to the back-end stage.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Depending on the physical technology (FPGA, ASIC gate array, ASIC standard cell), HDLs may or may not play a significant role in the back-end flow.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] In general, as the design flow progresses toward a physically realizable form, the design database becomes progressively more laden with technology-specific information, which cannot be stored in a generic HDL description.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Finally, an integrated circuit is manufactured or programmed for use.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Essential to HDL design is the ability to simulate HDL programs.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Simulation allows an HDL description of a design (called a model) to pass design verification, an important milestone that validates the design's intended function (specification) against the code implementation in the HDL description.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] It also permits architectural exploration.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] A designer can experiment with design choices by writing multiple variations of a base design, then comparing their behavior in simulation.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Thus, simulation is critical for successful HDL design.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] To simulate an HDL model, a designer writes a top-level simulation environment (called a test bench).
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] At minimum, a testbench contains an instantiation of the model (called the device under test or DUT), pin/signal declarations for the model's input/output (I/O), and a clock waveform.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The testbench code is event driven: a designer writes HDL statements to implement the (testbench-generated) reset-signal, to model interface transactions (such as a host–bus read/write), and to monitor the DUT's output.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] An HDL simulator — the program that executes the testbench — maintains the simulator clock, which is the master reference for all events in the testbench simulation.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Events occur only at the instants dictated by the testbench HDL (such as a reset-toggle coded into the testbench), or in reaction (by the model) to stimulus and triggering events.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Modern HDL simulators have full-featured graphical user interfaces, complete with a suite of debug tools.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] These allow the user to stop and restart the simulation at any time, insert simulator breakpoints (independent of the HDL code), and monitor or modify any element in the HDL model hierarchy.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Modern simulators can also link the HDL environment to user-compiled libraries, through a defined PLI/VHPI interface.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Linking is system-dependent (x86, SPARC etc. running Windows/Linux/Solaris), as the HDL simulator and user libraries are compiled and linked outside the HDL environment.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Design verification is often the most time-consuming portion of the design process, due to the disconnect between a device's functional specification, the designer's interpretation of the specification, and the imprecision of the HDL language.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Most of the initial test/debug cycle is conducted in the HDL *simulator* environment, as the early stage of the design is subject to frequent and major circuit changes.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] An HDL description can also be prototyped and tested in hardware — programmable logic devices are often used for this purpose.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Hardware prototyping is comparatively more expensive than HDL simulation, but offers a real-world view of the design.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Prototyping is the best way to check interfacing against other hardware devices and hardware prototypes.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Even those running on slow FPGAs offer much shorter simulation times than pure HDL simulation.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Historically, design verification was a laborious, repetitive loop of writing and running simulation test cases against the design under test.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] As chip designs have grown larger and more complex, the task of design verification has grown to the point where it now dominates the schedule of a design team.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Looking for ways to improve design productivity, the electronic design automation industry developed the Property Specification Language.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] In formal verification terms, a property is a factual statement about the expected or assumed behavior of another object.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Ideally, for a given HDL description, a property or properties can be proven true or false using formal mathematical methods.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] In practical terms, many properties cannot be proven because they occupy an unbounded solution space.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] However, if provided a set of operating assumptions or constraints, a property checker can prove (or disprove) certain properties by narrowing the solution space.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The assertions do not model circuit activity, but capture and document the designer's intent in the HDL code.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] In a simulation environment, the simulator evaluates all specified assertions, reporting the location and severity of any violations.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] In a synthesis environment, the synthesis tool usually operates with the policy of halting synthesis upon any violation.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Assertion based verification is still in its infancy, but is expected to become an integral part of the HDL design toolset.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] An HDL is grossly similar to a software programming language, but there are major differences.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Most programming languages are inherently procedural (single-threaded), with limited syntactical and semantic support to handle concurrency.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] HDLs, on the other hand, resemble concurrent programming languages in their ability to model multiple parallel processes (such as flip-flops and adders) that automatically execute independently of one another.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Any change to the process's input automatically triggers an update in the simulator's process stack.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Both programming languages and HDLs are processed by a compiler (often called a synthesizer in the HDL case), but with different goals.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] For HDLs, "compiling" refers to logic synthesis; the process of transforming the HDL code listing into a physically realizable gate netlist.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] On the other hand, a software compiler converts the source-code listing into a microprocessor-specific object code for execution on the target microprocessor.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] As HDLs and programming languages borrow concepts and features from each other, the boundary between them is becoming less distinct.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] However, pure HDLs are unsuitable for general purpose application software development, just as general-purpose programming languages are undesirable for modeling hardware.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Yet as electronic systems grow increasingly complex, and reconfigurable systems become increasingly common, there is growing desire in the industry for a single language that can perform some tasks of both hardware design and software programming.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] SystemC is an example of such—embedded system hardware can be modeled as non-detailed architectural blocks (black boxes with modeled signal inputs and output drivers).
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The target application is written in C or C++ and natively compiled for the host-development system; in contrast to targeting the embedded CPU, which requires host-simulation of the embedded CPU or an emulated CPU.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The high level of abstraction of SystemC models is well suited to early architecture exploration, as architectural modifications can be easily evaluated with little concern for signal-level implementation issues.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] However, the threading model used in SystemC relies on shared memory, causing the language not to handle parallel execution or low-level models well.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] In their level of abstraction, HDLs have been compared to assembly languages.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] There are attempts to raise the abstraction level of hardware design in order to reduce the complexity of programming in HDLs, creating a sub-field called *high-level synthesis*.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Companies such as Cadence, Synopsys and Agility Design Solutions are promoting SystemC as a way to combine high-level languages with concurrency models to allow faster design cycles for field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) than is possible using traditional HDLs.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Approaches based on standard C or C++ (with libraries or other extensions allowing parallel programming) are found in the Catapult C tools from Mentor Graphics, and the Impulse C tools from Impulse Accelerated Technologies.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] A similar initiative from Intel is the use of Data Parallel C++, related to SYCL, as a high-level synthesis language.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] It is also possible to design hardware modules using MATLAB and Simulink using the MathWorks HDL Coder tool or DSP Builder for Intel FPGAs or Xilinx System Generator (XSG) from Xilinx.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] The two most widely used and well-supported HDL varieties used in industry are Verilog and VHDL.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Several projects exist for defining printed circuit board connectivity using language based, textual-entry methods.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] Among these, new approaches have emerged that focus on enhancing readability, reusability, and validation.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] These modern methodologies employ open-source design languages specifically tailored for electronics, adopting declarative markup to specify what circuits should achieve.
[src:vhdl-design/hardware-description-language] This shift integrates software development principles into hardware design, streamlining the process and emphasizing automation, reuse, and validation.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] In 1983, VHDL was originally developed at the behest of the U.S.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Department of Defense in order to document the behavior of the ASIC that supplier companies were including in equipment.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The standard MIL-STD-454N in Requirement 64 in section 4.5.1 "ASIC documentation in VHDL" explicitly requires documentation of "Microelectronic Devices" in VHDL.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The idea of being able to simulate the ASICs from the information in this documentation was so obviously attractive that logic simulators were developed that could read the VHDL files.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The next step was the development of logic synthesis tools that read the VHDL and output a definition of the physical implementation of the circuit.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Due to the Department of Defense requiring as much of the syntax as possible to be based on Ada, in order to avoid re-inventing concepts that had already been thoroughly tested in the development of Ada, VHDL borrows heavily from the Ada programming language in both concept and syntax.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The initial version of VHDL, designed to IEEE standard IEEE 1076–1987, included a wide range of data types, including numerical (integer and real), logical (bit and Boolean), character and time, plus arrays of `bit` called `bit_vector` and of `character` called string.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] A problem not solved by this edition, however, was *multi-valued logic*, where a signal's drive strength (none, weak or strong) and unknown values are also considered.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] This required IEEE standard 1164, which defined the 9-value logic types: scalar `std_logic` and its vector version `std_logic_vector`.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Being a resolved subtype of its `std_Ulogic` parent type, `std_logic`-typed signals allow multiple driving for modeling bus structures, whereby the connected resolution function handles conflicting assignments adequately.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The updated IEEE 1076, in 1993, made the syntax more consistent, allowed more flexibility in naming, extended the `character` type to allow ISO-8859-1 printable characters, added the `xnor` operator, etc.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Minor changes in the standard (2000 and 2002) added the idea of protected types (similar to the concept of class in C++) and removed some restrictions from port mapping rules.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] In addition to IEEE standard 1164, several child standards were introduced to extend functionality of the language.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] IEEE standard 1076.2 added better handling of real and complex data types.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] IEEE standard 1076.3 introduced signed and unsigned types to facilitate arithmetical operations on vectors.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] IEEE standard 1076.1 (known as VHDL-AMS) provided analog and mixed-signal circuit design extensions.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Some other standards support wider use of VHDL, notably **VITAL** (VHDL Initiative Towards ASIC Libraries) and microwave circuit design extensions.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] In June 2006, the VHDL Technical Committee of Accellera (delegated by IEEE to work on the next update of the standard) approved so-called Draft 3.0 of VHDL-2006.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] While maintaining full compatibility with older versions, this proposed standard provides numerous extensions that make writing and managing VHDL code easier.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] These changes should improve quality of synthesizable VHDL code, make testbenches more flexible, and allow wider use of VHDL for system-level descriptions.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] In February 2008, Accellera approved VHDL 4.0, also informally known as VHDL 2008, which addressed more than 90 issues discovered during the trial period for version 3.0 and includes enhanced generic types.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] In 2008, Accellera released VHDL 4.0 to the IEEE for balloting for inclusion in IEEE 1076–2008.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The VHDL standard IEEE 1076-2008 was published in January 2009.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The IEEE Standard 1076 defines the VHSIC Hardware Description Language, or VHDL.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] It was originally developed under contract F33615-83-C-1003 from the United States Air Force awarded in 1983 to a team of Intermetrics, Inc. as language experts and prime contractor, Texas Instruments as chip design experts and IBM as computer-system design experts.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The language has undergone numerous revisions and has a variety of sub-standards associated with it that augment or extend it in important ways.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] IEEE Standard 1076 was and continues to be a milestone in the design of electronic systems.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] VHDL is generally used to write text models that describe a logic circuit.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Such a model is processed by a synthesis program only if it is part of the logic design.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] A simulation program is used to test the logic design using simulation models to represent the logic circuits that interface to the design.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] This collection of simulation models is commonly called a *testbench*.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] A VHDL simulator is typically an event-driven simulator.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] This means that each transaction is added to an event queue for a specific scheduled time.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] For example, if a signal assignment should occur after 1 nanosecond, the event is added to the queue for time +1ns.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Zero delay is also allowed, but still needs to be scheduled: for these cases, delta delay is used, which represents an infinitely small time step.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The simulation alternates between two modes: statement execution, where triggered statements are evaluated, and event processing, where events in the queue are processed.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] VHDL has constructs to handle the parallelism inherent in hardware designs, but these constructs (*processes*) differ in syntax from the parallel constructs in Ada (*tasks*).
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Like Ada, VHDL is strongly typed and is not case sensitive.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] In order to directly represent operations which are common in hardware, there are many features of VHDL which are not found in Ada, such as an extended set of Boolean operators including *nand* and *nor*.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] VHDL has file input and output capabilities, and can be used as a general-purpose language for text processing, but files are more commonly used by a simulation testbench for stimulus or verification data.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] There are some VHDL compilers that build executable binaries.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] In this case, it might be possible to use VHDL to write a *testbench* to verify the functionality of the design using files on the host computer to define stimuli, to interact with the user, and to compare results with those expected.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] However, most designers leave this job to the simulator.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] It is relatively easy for an inexperienced developer to produce code that simulates successfully, but that cannot be synthesized into a real device, or is too large to be practical.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] One particular pitfall is the accidental production of transparent latches rather than D-type flip-flops as storage elements.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] One can design hardware in a VHDL IDE (for FPGA implementation, such as Xilinx ISE, Altera Quartus, Synopsys Synplify, or Mentor Graphics HDL Designer) to produce the RTL schematic of the desired circuit.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] After that, the generated schematic can be verified using simulation software, which shows the waveforms of inputs and outputs of the circuit after generating the appropriate testbench.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] To generate an appropriate testbench for a particular circuit or VHDL code, the inputs have to be defined correctly.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] For example, for clock input, a loop process or an iterative statement is required.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] When a VHDL model is translated into the gates and wires that are mapped onto a programmable logic device such as a CPLD or FPGA, then it is the actual hardware being configured, rather than the VHDL code being executed as if on some form of a processor chip.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The key advantage of VHDL, when used for systems design, is that it allows the behavior of the required system to be described (modeled) and verified (simulated) before synthesis tools translate the design into real hardware (gates and wires).
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Another benefit is that VHDL allows the description of a concurrent system.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] VHDL is a dataflow language in which every statement is considered for execution simultaneously, unlike procedural computing languages such as BASIC, C, and assembly language, where a sequence of statements is run sequentially, one instruction at a time.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Being created once, a calculation block can be used in many other projects.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] However, many formational and functional block parameters can be tuned (capacity parameters, memory size, element base, block composition and interconnection structure).
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Being created for one element base, a computing device project can be ported to another element base; for example, VLSI with various technologies.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] A big advantage of VHDL compared to original Verilog is that VHDL has a full type system.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Designers can use the type system to write much more structured code (especially by declaring record types).
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] In VHDL, a design consists at a minimum of an *entity* which describes the interface and an *architecture* which contains the actual implementation.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] In addition, most designs import library modules.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Some designs also contain multiple architectures and *configurations*.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] (Notice that `RTL` stands for *Register transfer level* design.) While the example above may seem verbose to HDL beginners, many parts are either optional or need to be written only once.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Generally, simple functions like this are part of a larger behavioral module, instead of having a separate module for something so simple.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] In addition, use of elements such as the `std_logic` type might at first seem to be an overkill.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] One could easily use the built-in `bit` type and avoid the library import in the beginning.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] However, using a form of many-valued logic, specifically 9-valued logic (`U`,`X`,`0`,`1`,`Z`,`W`,`H`,`L`,`-`), instead of simple bits (0,1) offers a very powerful simulation and debugging tool to the designer which currently does not exist in any other HDL.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] In the examples that follow, one will see that VHDL code can be written in a very compact form.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] However, more experienced designers usually avoid these compact forms and use a more verbose coding style for the sake of readability and maintainability.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] VHDL is frequently used for two different goals: simulation of electronic designs and synthesis of such designs.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Synthesis is a process where a VHDL is compiled and mapped into an implementation technology such as an FPGA or an ASIC.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Not all constructs in VHDL are suitable for synthesis.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] For example, most constructs that explicitly deal with timing, such as `wait for 10 ns;` are not synthesizable despite being valid for simulation.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] While different synthesis tools have different capabilities, there exists a common *synthesizable subset* of VHDL that defines what language constructs and idioms map into common hardware for many synthesis tools.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] IEEE 1076.6 defines a subset of the language that is considered the official synthesis subset.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] It is generally considered a best practice to write very idiomatic code for synthesis as results can be incorrect or suboptimal for non-standard constructs.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The multiplexer, or 'MUX' as it is usually called, is a simple construct very common in hardware design.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The example below demonstrates a simple two-to-one MUX, with inputs `A` and `B`, selector `S` and output `X`.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Note that there are many other ways to express the same MUX in VHDL.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] A transparent latch is basically one bit of memory that is updated when an enable signal is raised.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Again, there are many other ways this can be expressed in VHDL.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The D-type flip-flop samples an incoming signal at the rising (or falling) edge of a clock.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] This example has an asynchronous, active-high reset and samples at the rising clock edge.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Another common way to write edge-triggered behavior in VHDL is with the 'event' signal attribute.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] A single apostrophe has to be written between the signal name and the name of the attribute.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Which can be useful if not all signals (registers) driven by this process should be reset.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The following example is an up-counter with asynchronous reset, parallel load and configurable width.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] It demonstrates the use of the 'unsigned' type, type conversions between 'unsigned' and 'std_logic_vector' and VHDL *generics*.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The generics are very close to arguments or templates in other traditional programming languages like C++.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] More complex counters may add if/then/else statements within the `rising_edge(CLK) elsif` to add other functions, such as count enables, stopping or rolling over at some count value, and generating output signals like terminal count signals.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Care must be taken with the ordering and nesting of such controls if used together, in order to produce the desired priorities and minimize the number of logic levels needed.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] A large subset of VHDL cannot be translated into hardware.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] This subset is known as the non-synthesizable or the simulation-only subset of VHDL and can only be used for prototyping, simulation and debugging.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] For example, the following code will generate a clock with a frequency of 50 MHz.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] It can, for example, be used to drive a clock input in a design during simulation.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] It is, however, a simulation-only construct and cannot be implemented in hardware.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] In actual hardware, the clock is generated externally; it can be scaled down internally by user logic or dedicated hardware.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] The simulation-only constructs can be used to build complex waveforms in a very short time.
[src:vhdl-design/ieee-1076] Such waveforms can be used, for example, as test vectors for a complex design or as a prototype of some synthesizer logic that will be implemented in the future.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] In digital circuit design, **register-transfer level** (**RTL**) is a design abstraction which models a synchronous digital circuit in terms of the flow of digital signals (data) between hardware registers, and the logical operations performed on those signals.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Register-transfer-level abstraction is used in hardware description languages (HDLs) like Verilog and VHDL to create high-level representations of a circuit, from which lower-level representations and ultimately actual wiring can be derived.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Design at the RTL level is typical practice in modern digital design.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Unlike in software compiler design, where the register-transfer level is an intermediate representation and at the lowest level, the RTL level is the usual input that circuit designers operate on.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] In circuit synthesis, an intermediate language between the input register transfer level representation and the target netlist is sometimes used.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Unlike in netlist, constructs such as cells, functions, and multi-bit registers are available.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Transaction-level modeling is a higher level of electronic system design.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] A synchronous circuit consists of two kinds of elements: registers (sequential logic) and combinational logic.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Registers (usually implemented as D flip-flops) synchronize the circuit's operation to the edges of the clock signal, and are the only elements in the circuit that have memory properties.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Combinational logic performs all the logical functions in the circuit and it typically consists of logic gates.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] For example, a very simple synchronous circuit is shown in the figure.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The inverter is connected from the output, Q, of a register to the register's input, D, to create a circuit that changes its state on each rising edge of the clock, clk.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] In this circuit, the combinational logic consists of the inverter.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] When designing digital integrated circuits with a hardware description language (HDL), the designs are usually engineered at a higher level of abstraction than transistor level (logic families) or logic gate level.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] In HDLs the designer declares the registers (which roughly correspond to variables in computer programming languages), and describes the combinational logic by using constructs that are familiar from programming languages such as if-then-else and arithmetic operations.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] This level is called *register-transfer level*.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The term refers to the fact that RTL focuses on describing the flow of signals between registers.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Using an EDA tool for synthesis, this description can usually be directly translated to an equivalent hardware implementation file for an ASIC or an FPGA.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The synthesis tool also performs logic optimization.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] At the register-transfer level, some types of circuits can be recognized.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] If there is a cyclic path of logic from a register's output to its input (or from a set of registers outputs to its inputs), the circuit is called a state machine or can be said to be sequential logic.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] If there are logic paths from a register to another without a cycle, it is called a pipeline.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] RTL is used in the logic design phase of the integrated circuit design cycle.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] An RTL description is usually converted to a gate-level description of the circuit by a logic synthesis tool.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The synthesis results are then used by placement and routing tools to create a physical layout.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Logic simulation tools may use a design's RTL description to verify its correctness.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The most accurate power analysis tools are available for the circuit level but unfortunately, even with switch- rather than device-level modelling, tools at the circuit level have disadvantages like they are either too slow or require too much memory thus inhibiting large chip handling.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The majority of these are simulators like SPICE and have been used by the designers for many years as performance analysis tools.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Due to these disadvantages, gate-level power estimation tools have begun to gain some acceptance where faster, probabilistic techniques have begun to gain a foothold.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] But it also has its trade off as speedup is achieved on the cost of accuracy, especially in the presence of correlated signals.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Over the years it has been realized that biggest wins in low power design cannot come from circuit- and gate-level optimizations whereas architecture, system, and algorithm optimizations tend to have the largest impact on power consumption.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Therefore, there has been a shift in the incline of the tool developers towards high-level analysis and optimization tools for power.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] This in no way implies that lower level tools are unimportant.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Instead, each layer of tools provides a foundation upon which the next level can be built.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The abstractions of the estimation techniques at a lower level can be used on a higher level with slight modifications.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] It is a technique based on the concept of gate equivalents.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The complexity of a chip architecture can be described approximately in terms of gate equivalents where gate equivalent count specifies the average number of reference gates that are required to implement the particular function.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The total power required for the particular function is estimated by multiplying the approximated number of gate equivalents with the average power consumed per gate.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Assign a complexity in terms of gate equivalents.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The number of GE’s for each unit type are either taken directly as an input from the user or are fed from a library.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] is the assumed average dissipated energy by a gate equivalent, when active.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] , denotes the average percentage of gates switching per clock cycle and is allowed to vary from function to function.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] , is a combination of fan-out loading as well as wiring.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] An estimate of the average wire length can be used to calculate the wiring capacitance.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The percentage of gates switching per clock cycle denoted by activity factors are assumed to be fixed regardless of the input patterns.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Typical gate switching energy is characterized by completely random uniform white noise (UWN) distribution of the input data.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] This implies that the power estimation is same regardless of the circuit being idle or at maximum load as this UWN model ignores how different input distributions affect the power consumption of gates and modules.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] denotes the loading due to a single cell hanging off the bit line.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The chosen activity factor gives the correct total power, but the breakdown of power into logic, clock, memory, etc. is less accurate.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Therefore this tool is not much different or improved in comparison with CES.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Where Ki is PFA proportionality constant that characterizes the ith functional element $G_{i}$ is the measure of hardware complexity, and $f_{i}$ denotes the activation frequency.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Gi denoting the hardware complexity of the multiplier is related to the square of the input word length i.e.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The activation frequency is the rate at which multiplies are performed by the algorithm denoted by $f_{mult}$ and the PFA constant, $K_{mult}$ , is extracted empirically from past multiplier designs and shown to be about 15 fW/bit2-Hz for a 1.2 μm technology at 5V.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The estimation error (relative to switch-level simulation) for a 16x16 multiplier is experimented and it is observed that when the dynamic range of the inputs does not fully occupy the word length of the multiplier, the UWN model becomes extremely inaccurate.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Granted, good designers attempt to maximize word length utilization.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] Still, errors in the range of 50-100% are not uncommon.
[src:vhdl-design/register-transfer-level] The figure clearly suggests a flaw in the UWN model.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] In automata theory, **sequential logic** is a type of logic circuit whose output depends on the present value of its input signals and on the sequence of past inputs, the input history.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] This is in contrast to *combinational logic*, whose output is a function of only the present input.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] That is, sequential logic has *state* (*memory*) while combinational logic does not.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] Sequential logic is used to construct finite-state machines, a basic building block in all digital circuitry.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] Virtually all circuits in practical digital devices are a mixture of combinational and sequential logic.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] A familiar example of a device with sequential logic is a television set with "channel up" and "channel down" buttons.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] Pressing the "up" button gives the television an input telling it to switch to the next channel above the one it is currently receiving.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] If the television is on channel 5, pressing "up" switches it to receive channel 6.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] However, if the television is on channel 8, pressing "up" switches it to channel "9".
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] In order for the channel selection to operate correctly, the television must be aware of which channel it is currently receiving, which was determined by past channel selections.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] The television stores the current channel as part of its *state*.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] When a "channel up" or "channel down" input is given to it, the sequential logic of the channel selection circuitry calculates the new channel from the input and the current channel.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] Digital sequential logic circuits are divided into synchronous and asynchronous types.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] In synchronous sequential circuits, the state of the device changes only at discrete times in response to a clock signal.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] In asynchronous circuits the state of the device can change at any time in response to changing inputs.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] Nearly all sequential logic today is *clocked* or *synchronous* logic.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] In a synchronous circuit, an electronic oscillator called a *clock* (or clock generator) generates a sequence of repetitive pulses called the *clock signal* which is distributed to all the memory elements in the circuit.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] The basic memory element in synchronous logic is the flip-flop.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] The output of each flip-flop only changes when triggered by the clock pulse, so changes to the logic signals throughout the circuit all begin at the same time, at regular intervals, synchronized by the clock.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] The output of all the storage elements (flip-flops) in the circuit at any given time, the binary data they contain, is called the *state* of the circuit.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] The state of the synchronous circuit only changes on clock pulses.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] At each cycle, the next state is determined by the current state and the value of the input signals when the clock pulse occurs.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] The main advantage of synchronous logic is its simplicity.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] The logic gates which perform the operations on the data require a finite amount of time to respond to changes to their inputs.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] The interval between clock pulses must be long enough so that all the logic gates have time to respond to the changes and their outputs "settle" to stable logic values before the next clock pulse occurs.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] As long as this condition is met (ignoring certain other details) the circuit is guaranteed to be stable and reliable.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] This determines the maximum operating speed of the synchronous circuit.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] However, asynchronous logic is more difficult to design and is subject to problems not encountered in synchronous designs.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] The main problem is that digital memory elements are sensitive to the order that their input signals arrive; if two signals arrive at a flip-flop or latch at almost the same time, which state the circuit goes into can depend on which signal gets to the gate first.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] Therefore, the circuit can go into the wrong state, depending on small differences in the propagation delays of the logic gates.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] This problem is not as severe in synchronous circuits because the outputs of the memory elements only change at each clock pulse.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] The interval between clock signals is designed to be long enough to allow the outputs of the memory elements to "settle" so they are not changing when the next clock comes.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] Therefore, the only timing problems are due to "asynchronous inputs"; inputs to the circuit from other systems which are not synchronized to the clock signal.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] Asynchronous sequential circuits are typically used only in a few critical parts of otherwise synchronous systems where speed is at a premium, such as parts of microprocessors and digital signal processing circuits.
[src:vhdl-design/sequential-logic] The design of asynchronous logic uses different mathematical models and techniques from synchronous logic, and is an active area of research.
[src:vhdl-design/vhdl-ams] The VHDL-AMS standard was created with the intent of enabling designers of analog and mixed signal systems and integrated circuits to create and use modules that encapsulate high-level behavioral descriptions as well as structural descriptions of systems and components.
[src:vhdl-design/vhdl-ams] VHDL-AMS is an industry standard modeling language for mixed signal circuits.
[src:vhdl-design/vhdl-ams] It provides both continuous-time and event-driven modeling semantics, and so is suitable for analog, digital, and mixed analog/digital circuits.
[src:vhdl-design/vhdl-ams] It is particularly well suited for verification of very complex analog, mixed-signal and radio frequency integrated circuits.
[src:vhdl-design/vhdl-ams] In VHDL-AMS, a design consists at a minimum of an *entity* which describes the interface and an *architecture* which contains the actual implementation.
